<subSubSection id="FC8E653B875BB10119E25248FD8BF848" pageId="20" pageNumber="213" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="B42B36B0875BB10119E25248FBCFFB12" blockId="20.[699,1293,1114,1538]" pageId="20" pageNumber="213">
<emphasis id="86E0EAA2875BB10119E25248FCC2FB8A" bold="true" box="[699,854,1114,1143]" pageId="20" pageNumber="213">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="73944D33875BB101183E5248FC95FB62" authority="Merriam, 1889" authorityName="Merriam" authorityYear="1889" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Perognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="20" pageNumber="213" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="spinatus">Perognathus spinatus Merriam, 1889</taxonomicName>
, 
<materialsCitation id="04FC3CED875BB101184F5294FB1DFB3A" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3802894360" pageId="20" pageNumber="213">“Lower Colorado River, California, 25 miles below [S] the Needles,”</materialsCitation>
San Bernardino Co., California, USA.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B42B36B0875BB10119E452E6FA9FF871" blockId="20.[699,1293,1114,1538]" lastBlockId="20.[88,1297,1545,3468]" pageId="20" pageNumber="213">
Based on detailed sequencing of nDNA and mtDNA genes, 
<taxonomicName id="73944D33875BB10118815309FBFCFAC1" authorityName="Merriam" authorityYear="1889" box="[984,1128,1307,1340]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Perognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="20" pageNumber="216" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="spinatus">C. spinatus</taxonomicName>
is the basal member of the Baja California Peninsula lineage of the “modern” clade of coarsehaired pocket mice. In addition to this species, the clade includes two closely related, chaparral-adapted coarse-haired species (
<taxonomicName id="73944D33875BB1011B8A501BFE1BF9D7" baseAuthorityName="Merriam" baseAuthorityYear="1889" box="[211,399,1545,1578]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Chaetodipus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="20" pageNumber="215" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="californicus">C. californicus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="73944D33875BB1011A84501BFDDEF9D7" baseAuthorityName="Merriam" baseAuthorityYear="1889" box="[477,586,1545,1578]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Chaetodipus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="20" pageNumber="215" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fallax">C. fallax</taxonomicName>
) and three closely related, sand-obligate smooth-haired species (C. ammophilus, 
<taxonomicName id="73944D33875BB101195E5022FD36F9AC" baseAuthorityName="Merriam" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[519,674,1584,1617]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Chaetodipus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="20" pageNumber="216" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="arenarius">C. arenarius</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="73944D33875BB10119AB5022FCF6F9AC" baseAuthorityName="Osgood" baseAuthorityYear="1907" box="[754,866,1584,1617]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Chaetodipus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="20" pageNumber="213" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="siccus">C. siccus</taxonomicName>
). Analysis of geographical variation in mtDNA throughoutthe distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="73944D33875BB10119A4504AFC19F984" authorityName="Merriam" authorityYear="1889" box="[765,909,1624,1657]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Perognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="20" pageNumber="216" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="spinatus">C. spinatus</taxonomicName>
, including eleven of the 13 known island populations (excluding evermanni on Mejia Island and guardiae on Isla Angel de la Guarda), revealed only three clades: a basal clade of occultus from Isla del Carmen; the Cape Region subspecies peninsulae and lamb: of Espiritu Santo Island; and all other peninsular and insular populations sampled, at least to south-eastern California, including the nominate subspecies. Based on the very low levels of genetic divergence indicated between and within the three clades, a subspecific revision would likely result in recognition of only three subspecies: occultus, peninsulae, and 
<taxonomicName id="73944D33875BB1011FC25179FA93F871" authorityName="Merriam" authorityYear="1889" box="[1179,1287,1899,1932]" class="Mammalia" family="Heteromyidae" genus="Perognathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="20" pageNumber="213" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="spinatus">spinatus</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B42B36B0875BB1011B035186FD8BF848" blockId="20.[88,1297,1545,3468]" box="[90,543,1940,1973]" pageId="20" pageNumber="213">Eighteen subspecies recognized.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
